        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Technical Justification
Requested sensitivity: 
We aim to have a spatial resolution of 0.5’’, corresponding to 42 pc at the distance of NGC 613. The main-beam temperature of HCN 1-0 toward the center of NGC 613 with SEST (HPBW=57”) is Tmb ~ 0.006 (=TA*/ηmb) K (figure 3, Lindberg et al. 2011),  where antenna temperature (TA*) is 0.0045 K and main-beam efficiency (ηmb) 0.75. In case that the distribution of HCN 1-0 corresponds to that of H2 1-0 S(1), most of HCN line is emitted in the radius of r ~ 0.75’’ from the center (figure 2). The expected temperature is about 8.66 (=0.006*(57/1.5)^2) K. We therefore need a noise level of 1.5 K at 5 km/s for achieving 6σ detection. We observe in dual polarization to obtain maximum sensitivity. We require total 12-m array time of 34.29 min (8.75 min per field) taking into account fraction of overhead time, and total time for science goal including ACA and TP time of 3.14 hr, according to Observation Tool for ALMA. The expected temperatures of HCO+ 1-0, CS 2-1, SiO 2-1 are 10.7 K, 5.33 K and 1.95 K, respectively, adopting that the measured line rations of HCO+/HCN~1.23 and CS/HCN~0.62 in NGC 4945 (Wang et al. 2004) and SiO/HCN~0.225 in NGC 1068 (Garcia-Burillo et al. 2010). Given the width of the emission of ∼ 350 km/s, for the faintest SiO emission we can degrade the spectral resolution to ∼ 0.47 K (at 50 km/s) in order to achieve &gt;4 σ detection, and even better in the integrated maps. This sensitivity is enough to detect 100 GHz continuum flux of &gt; several 10 mJy assumed from the flux of NGC 1084, whose luminosity in far infrared is almost equivalent with it of NGC 613 (Sanders et al. 2003). 


Imaging requirements: 
We propose to observe toward one pointing to cover the nuclear ring as well as the circum-nuclear disk of NGC 613. We estimate largest extent of the proposed molecular gas (~40 arcsec) from it of CO 1-0, which have been only reported (figure2, Bahaha et al. 1995, Lindberg et al. 2011). ACA is therefore required to image the gas. The declination of NGC 613 is of -29d25m06s. Using CASA simulator, it is confirmed that good map is produced owing to good (u, v) coverage.

Correlator setup: 
We observe HCN and HCO+ 1-0, SiO 2-1, CS 2-1 and the 100-GHz continuum in Band 3. 
It is estimated that the expected velocity widths of the spectra are about 350 km/s at most (figure 3). 
We choose 937.5 MHz (~3180 km/s) bandwidth for HCN and HCO+, 1875 MHz (~5621 km/s) bandwidth for SiO and 234.375 MHz (721 km/s) bandwidth for CS. 
We smooth the lines to 5 km/s to improve signal to noise ratio. 
We select 1875 MHz bandwidth and 976 kHz resolution for continuum so as to remove narrow lines in the continuum.
